SIMPLE: try
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Try
<hw>Try</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>tried</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Trying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>trien</ets> to select,
pick out, F. <ets>trier</ets> to cull, to out, LL. <ets>tritare</ets> to
triturate (hence the sense of, to thresh, to separate the grain from the
straw, to select), L. <ets>terere</ets>, <ets>tritum</ets>, to rub,
bruise, grind, thresh. See <er>Trite</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
divide or separate, as one sort from another; to winnow; to sift; to
pick out; -- frequently followed by <xex>out</xex>; <as>as, to
<ex>try</ex> out the wild corn from the good</as>.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir T. Elyot.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To purify or refine, as metals; to melt out, and
procure in a pure state, as oil, tallow, lard, etc.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The words of the Lord are pure words: as silver <qex>tried</qex>
in a furnace of earth, purified seven times.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. xii.
6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For thou, O God, hast proved us: thou hast <qex>tried</qex> us, as
silver is <qex>tried</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. lxvi. 10.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To prove by experiment; to apply a test to, for the
purpose of determining the quality; to examine; to prove; to test;
<as>as, to <ex>try</ex> weights or measures by a standard; to
<ex>try</ex> a man's opinions</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let the end <qex>try</qex> the man.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To subject to severe trial; to put to the test; to
cause suffering or trouble to.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thus far to <qex>try</qex> thee, Adam, I was pleased.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These are the times that try men's souls.</q> <qau>Thomas Paine
(1776)</qau>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1548 --></p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To experiment with; to test by use; <as>as, to
<ex>try</ex> a remedy for disease; to <ex>try</ex> a
horse</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Come, <qex>try</qex> upon yourselves what you have seen me.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To ease her cares the force of sleep she <qex>tries</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To strain; to subject to excessive tests; <as>as,
the light <ex>tries</ex> his eyes</as>; repeated disappointments
<xex>try</xex> one's patience.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>To examine or investigate
judicially; to examine by witnesses or other judicial evidence and the
principles of law; <as>as, to <ex>try</ex> a cause, or a
criminal</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To settle; to decide; to determine; specifically, to
decide by an appeal to arms; <as>as, to <ex>try</ex> rival claims by a
duel; to <ex>try</ex> conclusions</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Left I the court, to see this quarrel <qex>tried</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>To experience; to have or gain knowledge of by
experience.</def> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Or <qex>try</qex> the Libyan heat or Scythian cold.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>To essay; to attempt; to endeavor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let us <qex>try</qex> . . . to found a path.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To try on</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To put on, as a
garment, to ascertain whether it fits the person.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd>
<cd>To attempt; to undertake.</cd> <mark>[Slang]</mark>
<au>Dickens.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To attempt; endeavor; strive; aim; examine.</syn>
<usage> -- <er>Try</er>, <er>Attempt</er>. To <xex>try</xex> is the
generic, to <xex>attempt</xex> is the specific, term. When we
<xex>try</xex>, we are usually uncertain as to success; when we
<xex>attempt</xex>, we have always some definite object in view which we
seek to accomplish. We may be indifferent as to the result of a
<xex>trial</xex>, but we rarely <xex>attempt</xex> anything without a
desire to succeed.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He first deceased: she for a little <qex>tried</qex>⟦br⟧
To live without him; liked it not, and died.</q> <rj><qau>Sir H.
Wotton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Alack, I am afraid they have a waked,⟦br⟧
And 't is not done. The <qex>attempt</qex>, and not the deed,⟦br⟧
Confounds us.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Try</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Try
<hw>Try</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To exert
strength; to endeavor; to make an effort or an attempt; <as>as, you must
<ex>try</ex> hard if you wish to learn</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To do; to fare; <as>as, how do you
<ex>try</ex></as>!</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Try</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Try
<hw>Try</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A screen, or sieve, for
grain.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Prov. Eng.]</mark>
<rj><au>Holland.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Act of trying; attempt; experiment; trial.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This breaking of his has been but a <qex>try</qex> for his
friends.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>In Rugby and Northern Union football, a score
(counting three points) made by grounding the ball on or behind the
opponent's goal line; -- so called because it entitles the side making
it to a place kick for a goal (counting two points more if
successful).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Try</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Try
<hw>Try</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <er>Try</er>, <pos>v.
t.</pos>]</ety> <def>Refined; select; excellent; choice.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Sugar that is <xex>try</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Try cock</ent>⟦br⟧
